# C# Conventions

- Use `async`/`await` throughout ‚Äî no `.Result` or `.Wait()`
- Return `IActionResult` or `ActionResult<T>` from controller actions
- Use `var` when the type is obvious from the right-hand side
- Prefer `record` types for DTOs; use classes for entities
- Keep controllers thin ‚Äî business logic belongs in services

## Example: async controller action
```csharp
// ‚úÖ Correct
[HttpGet("{id}")]
public async Task<ActionResult<ToDoDto>> GetToDo(int id)
{
    var item = await _service.GetByIdAsync(id);
    return item is null ? NotFound() : Ok(item);
}

// ‚ùå Avoid blocking calls
public ActionResult<ToDoDto> GetToDo(int id)
{
    var item = _service.GetByIdAsync(id).Result;
    return Ok(item);
}
```

## Example: DTO vs entity
```csharp
// ‚úÖ DTO as a record ‚Äî immutable, no EF tracking concerns
public record ToDoDto(int Id, string Description, string Status, DateOnly? DueDate);

// ‚úÖ Entity as a class ‚Äî EF Core needs a parameterless constructor
public class ToDo : Entry
{
    public DateOnly? DueDate { get; set; }
    public TimeOnly? DueTime { get; set; }
}
```
